We appreciate the police for keeping our military culture alive, we hope our enemies are quaking in their boots after seeing how tough our officers can be when dealing with law breakers.
As we go into 2021, our wish is to see a police service that is kinder to suffering Kenyans and more humane in their handling of suspected law breakers. We did not see them raise a finger against the Big Five politicians who broke Covid-19 guidelines like their life depended on it, even though those super-spreader events put the lives of many Kenyans in danger.
While ordinary Kenyans do not expect to be massaged while being led to safety whenever they break the law, at least the police can stop slapping unarmed civilians in front of their loved ones to prove that they are better bullies. 
There are better ways to demonstrate misguided machismo, and pointing a gun to someone’s temple isn’t one of them. If you must kill anything to prove to your bosses that you’re doing a good job, kill the urge to demand a bribe before you offer a service you are paid to give.
In 2021, Kenyans also expect government officials to reduce the amount of salt they add while enumerating the gains they have made, because health experts have warned us that too much salt is a risk factor in cardiovascular diseases.



